http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/Water-and-waste-management-in-focus/article13979331.ece

Water and waste management as well as volunteer participation took the centre stage on the second day of ‘Yadhum Oore’ conference organised by the Agaram Foundation, The Hindu and Puthiya Thalamurai channel.The day began with a session on the need to bring about changes in water resource management, which had G. Sakthinathan from Anna University speak on water management and its practicability; Arun Krishnamurthi from Environment Foundation of India speak about volunteer participation in the maintenance of lakes and Sekar Raghavan from Rain Centre shedding light on rainwater harvesting in urban households.Participants said that sessions by the members of ‘Siruthuli,’ a Coimbatore-based NGO on terrace gardens and solid waste management, had inspired them.“Plastics still pose a big threat to the environment and an initiative like this can go a long way,” said Valli Devi of Chromepet.Dharani, an employee with Railways, who participated in the conference, said it was up to volunteers and willing participants to take the process of awareness creation further.Actor Surya, founder of Agaram Foundation, said four key action points that emerged during the conference were environmental literacy, tree plantation and preservation, conservation of waterbodies and responsible waste management.All the participants took a pledge in this regard.Volunteers who were active during the floods were felicitated by N. Ram, Chairman of Kasturi and Sons Limited. Justice N. Kirubakaran of Madras High Court and writer Bharathi Krishnakumar addressed the valedictory function.